{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 18:19:07.499938", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nNetwork / scope\n- Hierarchical enterprise network using OSPF; user hosts in 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24; central server farm 10.200.0.0/24 (dns_server 10.200.0.2, load_balancer 10.200.0.7, web_server_0..3 .3-.6, dhcp .8).\n- server_access_router connects server farm and participates in OSPF with other routers (server networks advertised into OSPF).\n\nSummary conclusion (high-level)\n- The network is largely healthy: IP-level reachability between hosts and servers is working (no packet loss observed in the reachability test sample). OSPF routes are present and being used.\n- Two notable abnormal findings require attention:\n  1) Backend web servers in 10.200.0.0/24 are directly reachable from user hosts — this contradicts the stated design (“backend web servers should not be directly accessible from the hosts”).\n  2) HTTP client behavior observed from a test host shows an anomalous curl return code of 000 despite receiving HTML content; this suggests an atypical HTTP behavior (e.g., missing/partial HTTP status line / HTTP/0.9 or early connection close) from the web service path.\n\nEvidence and observations (tests performed)\n1) Global reachability scan (get_reachability)\n- The automated reachability results show successful pings between servers and many hosts across the network with 0% packet loss in sampled tests. Latencies vary, but connectivity is available across subnets.\n\n2) Name resolution\n- From host_1_1_1_1: nslookup web99.local 10.200.0.2 -> web99.local resolves to 10.200.0.7 (load balancer). DNS resolution is functioning.\n\n3) ICMP reachability from a host to servers\n- From host_1_1_1_1:\n  - ping to dns_server (10.200.0.2): avg RTT ≈ 3.57 ms, 0% loss.\n  - ping to load_balancer (10.200.0.7): avg RTT ≈ 3.41 ms, 0% loss.\n  - ping to web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): 4/4 replies, avg RTT ≈ 7.37 ms, with an outlier sample (max ≈ 15.4 ms). Connectivity is present.\n\n4) HTTP functional test (curl)\n- From host_1_1_1_1:\n  - curl http://web99.local/ (using DNS) produced HTML content but curl reported HTTP code \"000\" in the formatted output.\n  - curl http://10.200.0.3/ (direct to backend IP) produced similar behavior: HTML content returned, but curl reported HTTP code \"000\".\n- Observed behavior: page content is delivered to the client host, but curl’s reported HTTP status is 000 (meaning curl did not see a proper HTTP status line to parse a numeric code). The raw HTML content (a large/mock page) was received.\n\n5) Server interface and routing\n- web_server_0 ifconfig/ip route:\n  - eth0: 10.200.0.3/24, default via 10.200.0.1 (gateway in server subnet).\n- server_access_router OSPF / routing:\n  - OSPF: server_access_router is attached to area 0.0.0.0; area shows networks and LSAs.\n  - Routing table: 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected on br0 and being advertised via OSPF. Routes to all 10.1.x.x and 10.2.x.x host subnets are present via a neighbor (172.16.0.22) and reachable.\n\nAnomalies / abnormal behavior (detailed)\n1) Backend exposure — policy/segmentation breach\n- Design statement: backend web servers should not be directly accessible from hosts; only load balancer (web99.local) should be the published front-end.\n- Observation: Hosts can resolve and directly reach backend web server IPs (10.200.0.3 etc.) and can retrieve content directly from them (curl to backend IP returned HTML). OSPF advertisement and routing make the server subnet reachable from user subnets.\n- Localization: The server_access_router (the router directly connecting 10.200.0.0/24) and the OSPF/routing configuration across the core/distribution layer are the place where reachability is realized. Because 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected to server_access_router and is being advertised by OSPF, any host with OSPF-learned routes can reach those addresses. If segmentation was intended, the filtering is missing (i.e., ACLs, firewall rules, or the servers placed in a non-advertised/isolated network). So the responsible device(s) for the immediate lack of isolation are:\n  - server_access_router (direct connection + advertisement)\n  - core/distribution routers that accept/propagate the OSPF advertisement without filtering\n  - any missing firewall or ACL appliance that should have enforced the intended policy\n\n2) Unexpected HTTP status behavior (curl returns 000)\n- Symptom: curl’s formatted output shows HTTP status code 000 while the response body (HTML) is nonetheless received.\n- Interpretation: HTTP status 000 from curl indicates that curl did not capture a valid numeric HTTP status line. Possible causes include:\n  - The server (or some device in path) is responding with HTTP/0.9-style responses (raw HTML without HTTP headers/status line).\n  - The server or an in-path proxy/load-balancer is closing the connection before sending the status line, or producing non-standard HTTP framing.\n  - Intermittent protocol/transport issues causing curl to be unable to parse the status line even though data (body) is received.\n- Localization: The anomaly appeared when connecting through both the load balancer hostname and directly to a backend IP. That suggests the behavior originates at the web server or a service on the server_access_router/bridge (or possibly an HTTP proxy/load-balancer component used by the servers). The load_balancer (10.200.0.7) was also reachable and returned content; so either both the load balancer and backend servers have the same behavior, or some middlebox/bridge is altering the HTTP handshake.\n\nOther observations about health & performance\n- Latencies in ping tests are modest and variable across the topology but generally within expected lab/enterprise ranges for the topology size.\n- No packet loss was observed in the ping samples provided.\n- OSPF on server_access_router shows normal operation with area 0 active and LSAs present.\n\nRoot-cause hypotheses\n(1) Lack of intended isolation:\n- Root cause (most likely): Network-level routing advertisement and lack of filtering. The server_access_router directly connects 10.200.0.0/24 and that prefix is advertised via OSPF; core/distribution routers accept and forward those routes, enabling host-to-backend reachability. There is no evidence of any network ACLs or firewall that blocks direct traffic from user subnets to backend servers. This is a configuration/policy enforcement gap (devices responsible: server_access_router and upstream routers or missing firewall policy).\n\n(2) HTTP status 000 behavior:\n- Root cause (probable): Non-standard or incomplete HTTP response being returned by the service or by an intermediary (load balancer/proxy) — e.g., an HTTP/0.9 style response, or a connection close before/without sending an HTTP status line. Since this was reproducible both to the load balancer name and to a backend IP, the source could be the web servers themselves (they may be serving in an atypical mode) or a shared component in the server subnet (load balancer/backend service/process) that alters the protocol. This is an application-layer/proxy behavior rather than a pure IP routing problem.\n\nRecommended next data to collect (for diagnostics; not remediation)\n- Show FRR running configs and OSPF config on server_access_router and core routers (to confirm which networks are being advertised and whether any export/import filters or ACLs are expected).\n- Show any firewall/ACL configurations on server_access_router, core, or distribution routers, and any dedicated firewall/appliance in front of the server farm.\n- Capture a packet trace (tcpdump) of the HTTP exchange at:\n  - server_access_router interface toward the server subnet,\n  - at one backend web server (e.g., web_server_0) on eth0,\n  - at the load_balancer (eth0/eth1) — to see the HTTP request/response headers and determine whether a status line is present.\n- Check web server logs (web_server_0..3) and load_balancer logs to see what they log for the incoming requests and what status codes they report.\n- Inspect web server (Apache/nginx) configuration to see if any non-standard HTTP modes are enabled (HTTP/0.9 or custom socket responses).\n\nKey devices implicated (localization)\n- server_access_router: advertises 10.200.0.0/24 and is the immediate gateway for servers — primary localization for lack of segmentation.\n- Core/distribution routers: they propagate OSPF routes that provide reachability from user subnets — secondary localization for the policy propagation path.\n- load_balancer & web servers: implicated for the HTTP status anomaly (both load balancer and at least one backend respond with HTML yet curl reports code 000).\n\nFinal notes\n- At the network/IP level the infrastructure is operational (routes, OSPF, DNS, DHCP server reachable, ICMP working).\n- The most significant concern is policy: backends are reachable directly by hosts when the design expects them to be hidden. That makes this a security/segmentation deviation rather than a simple connectivity fault.\n- The HTTP/000 anomaly should be investigated at the application/proxy level with packet captures and server logs to determine whether the issue is a misconfiguration of the web servers/load balancer or an intermediate device altering the response.\n\nIf you want, I can proceed to collect the additional configuration and packet-level data listed above (FRR configs, firewall/ACL rules, tcpdump on server_access_router, and web server logs) to confirm the root causes.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 39843, "output_tokens": 3709, "total_tokens": 43552, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 38784}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1536}}}
